{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594524"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:49:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:49:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15320"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15320"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.1,0.3,0,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8011"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69324"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8011"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54777"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"571"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19484"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69324"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department. Blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAspartate aminotransferase (AST): 2500 U/L (10-40)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlanine aminotransferase (ALT): 2800 U/L (10-40)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlkaline phosphatase: 120 U/L (30-120)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGamma-glutamyl transferase: 80 U/L (5-50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETotal bilirubin: 45 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this liver enzyme pattern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paracetamol overdose","Acute biliary obstruction","Autoimmune hepatitis","Haemochromatosis","Primary biliary cholangitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVery high transaminases (\u003E20x upper reference limit) typically indicate acute hepatocellular injury. \u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol overdose\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of severe acute liver injury and characteristically leads to AST and ALT elevations \u003E1000 U/L within 24-48 hours of ingestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute biliary obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a cholestatic pattern with predominant alkaline phosphatase elevation and more modest transaminase elevation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with moderately elevated transaminases (5-10x normal) and a positive antinuclear antibody test\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemochromatosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic condition that typically causes mild transaminase elevation (\u003C5x normal) with elevated ferritin and transferrin saturation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary biliary cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with elevated alkaline phosphatase and mild transaminase elevation, often with positive antimitochondrial antibodies\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pattern of markedly elevated transaminases with relatively normal alkaline phosphatase is characteristic of acute hepatocellular injury. Other causes include acute viral hepatitis and ischaemic hepatitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Severe elevations in liver enzymes (\u003E20x upper limit) typically occur in acute hepatocellular injury from viral hepatitis, drug toxicity, or ischaemia","Paracetamol overdose characteristically causes AST and ALT elevations \u003E1000 U/L within 24-48 hours of ingestion","Chronic liver conditions like haemochromatosis typically cause mild to moderate enzyme elevations (\u003C5x upper limit)"],"references":["Chidiac AS, Buckley NA, Noghrehchi F, Cairns R. Paracetamol (acetaminophen) overdose and hepatotoxicity: mechanism, treatment, prevention measures, and estimates of burden of disease. Expert Opin Drug Metab Toxicol. 2023 Jan-Jun;19(5):297-317. doi: 10.1080/17425255.2023.2223959. PMID: 37436926.","Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54777"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15320"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54777"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:39:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:41:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8011"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69324"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"h